1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,660
This video was made possible by Hover, professionalize your web presence with a custom domain and email address for 10% off at hover.com-slash-wendover.

2
00:00:10,359 --> 00:00:16,000
About 13 million times per day, someone clicks the order button on Amazon.com.

3
00:00:16,300 --> 00:00:22,379
Some days later, all, or at least almost all, of those 13 million orders arrive at their destination.

4
00:00:22,960 --> 00:00:28,379
But what happens in between? How does Amazon get a package to you?

5
00:00:28,379 --> 00:00:31,239
Well, it depends. A lot.

6
00:00:31,839 --> 00:00:40,079
In fact, Amazon's fulfillment system, their shipping system, is more complicated and convoluted than that of almost any logistics company.

7
00:00:40,460 --> 00:00:46,799
It's far more complicated than that of UPS or FedEx or DHL or any other major delivery company.

8
00:00:47,219 --> 00:00:56,579
In a counterintuitive way, this complicated and convoluted fulfillment system is a crucial component of this secret sauce that's driving Amazon's success.

9
00:00:56,579 --> 00:01:01,939
They're striving to make the consumer experience simple through behind-the-scenes complexity.

10
00:01:02,399 --> 00:01:07,500
So, back to the question, how does the Amazon package get to you? And the answer? It depends.

11
00:01:08,239 --> 00:01:12,299
It depends first on who's fulfilling the package, Amazon or the seller.

12
00:01:12,760 --> 00:01:19,480
About one-fourth of sales in the US are fulfilled directly by the seller, as most products on Amazon are listed there by a third party,

13
00:01:19,739 --> 00:01:25,599
which can send packages directly through UPS, FedEx, the Postal Service, or another consumer delivery company if they choose.

14
00:01:25,599 --> 00:01:33,280
Amazon has nothing to do with the fulfillment of those orders, and the process looks largely the same as with any other e-commerce company.

15
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:41,420
What's different is how the other three quarters of Amazon packages in the US get to you, the ones that are fulfilled directly by Amazon.

16
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:46,099
The path that these take depends first on how big the package is.

17
00:01:46,640 --> 00:01:54,959
You see, Amazon's fulfillment centers are more or less split into three categories, small-sortable, large-sortable, and large-non-sortable.

18
00:01:54,959 --> 00:02:00,420
That first category, small-sortable, represents the bread and butter of Amazon's business.

19
00:02:00,920 --> 00:02:10,060
These are items that are less than 12 by 16 by 6 inches, or 30 by 40 by 15 centimeters in size, and about 25 pounds or 11 kilograms in weight.

20
00:02:10,659 --> 00:02:17,400
The next category, large-sortable, is basically anything larger than this, up to a weight of about 60 pounds or 27 kilograms.

21
00:02:17,400 --> 00:02:25,479
Now, the reasons for the split between large and small is because the fulfillment operations of smaller items is much easier to automate.

22
00:02:25,960 --> 00:02:31,419
They can fit on conveyor belts and automated robots and other tools that lower the company's reliance on humans.

23
00:02:32,039 --> 00:02:41,699
For example, Amazon uses a robot called the Kiva, which fundamentally changed the way the job of the company's pickers, the people who find and grab an item out of storage, worked.

24
00:02:42,300 --> 00:02:49,020
Previously, pickers would walk some 10 to 12 miles or 16 to 19 kilometers a day through cavernous rows of shelves.

25
00:02:49,580 --> 00:03:00,020
Now, at least in their most advanced fulfillment centers, a robot picks up an entire mobile shelf on which a required product is located and transports it to the picker, who picks it.

26
00:03:00,419 --> 00:03:05,000
Essentially, rather than the picker going to the shelf, the shelf goes to the picker.

27
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:13,159
With these robots, one person can pick 3 to 400 items an hour, rather than the 100 or so that was possible on foot.

28
00:03:13,719 --> 00:03:22,659
Of course, fewer humans in the mix is good for Amazon, given the amount of criticism it receives for its treatment of workers, and because humans, even low-paid ones, are expensive.

29
00:03:23,659 --> 00:03:35,340
The fulfillment process for larger items, though, is just tougher to automate cheaply, so the company chooses to segment the two processes out and runs a far more manual and distinct fulfillment system for larger items.

30
00:03:35,860 --> 00:03:44,759
However, in most, but not all cases, the fulfillment centers for large and small items are under the same roof, even if they're operated completely independently.

31
00:03:44,759 --> 00:03:53,199
Of course, the ideal scenario for Amazon would be to have every single item they sell in every single warehouse, but that's not realistic.

32
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:59,680
Therefore, they use predictive modeling to try to put items closest to those who are likely to buy them.

33
00:04:00,120 --> 00:04:05,599
The US is far from homogeneous, so demand for different products varies from place to place.

34
00:04:05,599 --> 00:04:11,479
For example, in Miami, people probably aren't looking to buy many ice scrapers for their cars.

35
00:04:11,979 --> 00:04:16,939
Meanwhile, in Fargo, North Dakota, demand for this item is almost certainly quite high.

36
00:04:17,439 --> 00:04:24,420
It's therefore no wonder why that, if you look at the data, the colder the city, the faster you can get an ice scraper on Amazon.

37
00:04:25,060 --> 00:04:27,920
That is Amazon's predictive stalking at work.

38
00:04:28,480 --> 00:04:34,279
While most examples of the system are far more nuanced and far less intuitive, the concept is simple.

39
00:04:34,279 --> 00:04:41,980
Their algorithms put products closest to the consumers most likely to buy them, something only possible at this scale thanks to modern big data analytics.

40
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:48,079
Of course, there's then that third category of products, large, non-sortable.

41
00:04:48,500 --> 00:04:54,120
The distinction here is because Amazon likes to aggregate products together into as few packages as possible.

42
00:04:54,519 --> 00:04:57,439
Unsurprisingly, fewer packages equals lower costs.

43
00:04:57,439 --> 00:05:04,120
So, both these sortable categories include anything that could possibly be packaged together in a single box.

44
00:05:04,639 --> 00:05:11,279
The larger items, say a 70-pound bean bag, for example, are shipped from the large non-sortable fulfillment centers.

45
00:05:11,920 --> 00:05:19,660
These facilities are even less automated than the large sortable ones and even include workers who create custom boxes for odd-size items.

46
00:05:19,660 --> 00:05:27,579
In Colorado, for example, this is a completely separate facility, located in Aurora, from the sortable fulfillment center in Thornton.

47
00:05:28,040 --> 00:05:40,060
Now, some large items will go directly into the system of a third-party provider, typically XBO logistics, which would deliver these bulky items to their final destination, while others will continue on in Amazon system.

48
00:05:40,060 --> 00:05:50,899
The portion of large non-sortable items not sent to a third-party logistics provider plus all the large and small sortable packages would next be sent to a regional sortation center.

49
00:05:51,180 --> 00:05:59,759
In Colorado, those two fulfillment centers send their packages to a single sortation center, located just minutes away from the Aurora fulfillment center.

50
00:05:59,759 --> 00:06:10,980
This is a massive facility, almost half a million square feet in size, with robots running around, dropping packages into different shoots, which each represent a different grouping of zip codes.

51
00:06:11,639 --> 00:06:17,139
Now, not all these sortation centers are quite so automated, but each outputs the same thing.

52
00:06:17,699 --> 00:06:20,740
Palettes of packages going to roughly the same place.

53
00:06:21,379 --> 00:06:24,180
What happens next, though, once again, depends.

54
00:06:24,839 --> 00:06:38,980
A package heading to Miami, for example, would end up on a palette with other packages for Miami, which itself would end up on a truck carrying palettes for Tampa, North Carolina, Houston, Baltimore, New York City, Connecticut, and a few other cities and states to the east.

55
00:06:39,399 --> 00:06:47,660
This truck would then drive the 15 minutes to a waiting 767 cargo plane at Denver International Airport, branded in Prime Air Levering.

56
00:06:47,660 --> 00:06:58,740
Now, Amazon Air started in 2015 with its lease of about 20 aircraft from Air Transport International and has since grown to almost 70 aircraft, all leased from other airlines.

57
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:10,079
However, the company recently announced the purchase of their first 11 aircraft, also 767, bought from Delta and WestJet, meaning they'll soon both own and operate their own aircraft.

58
00:07:10,079 --> 00:07:17,360
Those eastbound palettes would all be loaded around 4am before the aircraft's scheduled departure time of 4.54am.

59
00:07:17,980 --> 00:07:24,199
Now, anyone familiar with UPS or FedEx's operations will know why this departure time is strange.

60
00:07:24,879 --> 00:07:37,899
If UPS was transporting this package to Miami, at least at its fastest speed, it would have departed on an aircraft the previous night at 9.40pm, been flown to Louisville, sorted through the company's hub, then flown to Miami, arriving at 5.50am.

61
00:07:37,899 --> 00:07:41,339
FedEx would have done roughly the same just through Memphis instead.

62
00:07:41,839 --> 00:07:47,360
That's because FedEx, UPS, and most other major delivery companies are oriented towards overnight delivery.

63
00:07:47,699 --> 00:07:54,839
They make a big chunk of their money, charging big rates to take a package from one part of the U.S. one day and deliver it to another the next day.

64
00:07:55,259 --> 00:08:03,660
Amazon, meanwhile, built their prime brand off the promise of two-day delivery, ordering a package on a Monday and getting it on a Wednesday, for example.

65
00:08:03,660 --> 00:08:16,740
While they've sent straight from the rigidness of that system, the fastest shipping they'll offer for an item not stocked at a local fulfillment center is two days, meaning they don't have to worry about being able to get a package from Denver to Miami overnight.

66
00:08:17,279 --> 00:08:22,220
That's why UPS and FedEx's planes take off in the evening, while Amazon's leave in the morning.

67
00:08:22,779 --> 00:08:29,680
So, that means it's about 9am by the time that Amazon airplane from Denver gets to Cincinnati Airport each day.

68
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:37,200
Through the morning hours, a dozen or so aircraft land in Cincinnati, and this timing gives the company a major advantage.

69
00:08:37,899 --> 00:08:52,639
Cincinnati Airport is also home to DHL's main America's hub, but DHL, like FedEx and UPS, conducts its operations primarily overnight starting at around midnight, when dozens of their aircraft from around the world land and unload.

70
00:08:52,639 --> 00:09:00,059
Over the next few hours, packages and pallets are sorted and unloaded onto other aircraft, which all tend to take off by 8am.

71
00:09:00,559 --> 00:09:07,840
That means DHL only really uses their facility during the overnight hours, so Amazon leases it for daytime use.

72
00:09:08,220 --> 00:09:15,179
While Amazon is building their own larger facility at Cincinnati Airport, this partnership gave them a huge head start.

73
00:09:15,179 --> 00:09:25,639
So, each day, between 8am and 4pm, Amazon's there, turning their planes around, and sorting pallets from where they come from, like Denver, to where they need to go, like Miami.

74
00:09:26,159 --> 00:09:33,080
That Miami flight takes off each weekday at 2pm, and then it lands in Florida just before 5pm Eastern time.

75
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:37,919
Now, not every Amazon air itinerary looks like this.

76
00:09:37,919 --> 00:09:51,259
In fact, while UPS and FedEx route almost all of their flights through their Louisville and Memphis super hubs, or through some of their secondary hubs across the country, only 20% of Amazon air's flights go through their main Cincinnati hub.

77
00:09:51,679 --> 00:09:57,700
That's because, with their orientation towards two-day delivery versus one, they just have more time.

78
00:09:58,440 --> 00:10:07,340
The more time means that, in order to service the entirety of Florida, Amazon only needs to fly to three destinations, Miami, Tampa, and Lakeland.

79
00:10:07,340 --> 00:10:17,340
That's because Amazon's flights to these airports typically land by 5pm, meaning there's a whole 12 hours before packages have to be at the local delivery center for the final destination.

80
00:10:18,460 --> 00:10:28,659
The entirety of Florida is within an 8-hour drive of Lakeland, meaning Amazon can deliver to all of Florida by only serving effectively one, but in practice three, airports.

81
00:10:29,259 --> 00:10:40,840
Meanwhile, FedEx, for example, flies from Memphis to Fort Lauderdale, Fort Myers, Jacksonville, Tallahassee, Tampa, and Palm Beach, then from Fort Lauderdale, it operates feeder flights on smaller aircraft to Key West and Marathon.

82
00:10:41,539 --> 00:10:49,220
So, in summary, in order to serve all of Florida, this is what FedEx has to do, and this is what Amazon has to do.

83
00:10:49,220 --> 00:11:00,720
The required number of destinations for full coverage is greatly reduced by orienting for two-day delivery, and this also means that Amazon doesn't have to route every flight via one main hub.

84
00:11:01,279 --> 00:11:10,639
Because they operate too far fewer destinations, it's much easier for Amazon to fill a plane from California, for example, exclusively with packages destined for Florida,

85
00:11:10,639 --> 00:11:21,279
since Wally giving UPS or FedEx flight carries packages from or to just one city, a given Amazon air flight likely carries packages from or to a whole state or region.

86
00:11:21,820 --> 00:11:34,419
Therefore, Amazon air has flights from all these airports to Lakeland, meaning that Wally package from Denver would have to route via Cincinnati, one from Los Angeles, or Dallas, or Chicago, could fly direct.

87
00:11:34,419 --> 00:11:52,019
With a full hub and spoke strategy, like that of UPS or FedEx, a package would have to be loaded and unloaded from aircraft twice, and sometimes more, while Amazon airs non-stop flights only require loading and unloading once, which reduces cost, and can fly packages direct, which also reduces cost.

88
00:11:52,580 --> 00:11:57,940
This is how Amazon can transport packages by air more efficiently than UPS or FedEx.

89
00:11:57,940 --> 00:12:05,659
The airplane, however, is just one of five routes that an Amazon package could take onwards from the Denver Sortation Center.

90
00:12:06,179 --> 00:12:12,539
For those that are to be delivered locally in the Denver area, they'll be driven to one of four delivery stations for Denver.

91
00:12:13,059 --> 00:12:21,580
There, they'll be loaded into smaller delivery vans, operated by independent companies or individuals contracted by Amazon, which will take the packages to their final destinations.

92
00:12:21,580 --> 00:12:33,379
This is the one and only case in which an Amazon package is handled by Amazon logistics from start to finish, and it's generally how their packages are delivered within major urban and suburban areas.

93
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:42,940
Only a slim majority of their overall package volume is delivered this way, though, as when you leave major urban areas, things get a bit more complicated.

94
00:12:43,940 --> 00:12:55,240
Now, a package heading outside the Denver area with a later delivery date or with a destination within the Greater Rockies region would end up on an Amazon branded, but independently operated, semi-truck.

95
00:12:55,700 --> 00:13:02,879
For example, packages to the Aspen area, about a three to four hour drive into the mountains, leave at around 1 a.m. each night.

96
00:13:03,399 --> 00:13:12,019
Early in the morning, however, at around 5 a.m., they arrive at the local post office, and from there, they're fully transferred into the United States Postal Service System,

97
00:13:12,019 --> 00:13:21,500
for final delivery. You see, in less populous areas, like the mountains of Colorado, it just doesn't make sense for Amazon to operate their own last mile delivering.

98
00:13:21,919 --> 00:13:30,000
They need a certain amount of scale for that to be cheaper than the alternative, and at least right now, that scale is only possible in major metro areas.

99
00:13:30,620 --> 00:13:38,360
Therefore, they need alternatives for smaller cities, towns, and rural areas, and that alternative is more often than not the USPS.

100
00:13:38,360 --> 00:13:46,860
That's because the Postal Service charges very low rates for last mile delivery, assuming Amazon transports the packages to the local post offices themselves.

101
00:13:47,600 --> 00:13:59,320
While exact numbers aren't publicly known, estimates indicate the USPS charges Amazon about $2 per package for last mile delivery, about half of what other delivery companies would for the same service.

102
00:13:59,320 --> 00:14:07,879
After all, the USPS services every address in America, so wherever Amazon needs to deliver, the USPS is going there anyways.

103
00:14:08,539 --> 00:14:18,039
That's why, for smaller places that still have a decent volume of packages, like mid-sized towns and cities, USPS delivery is often the cheapest option for Amazon.

104
00:14:19,039 --> 00:14:24,620
But then, there's that next step down, the most rural places in America.

105
00:14:25,240 --> 00:14:37,980
Everything that can't be cheaply delivered by Amazon or the USPS, typically because they're destined for low-density areas where you couldn't even fill a truck to send to the local post office, or because of capacity or speed reasons, is sent through UPS.

106
00:14:38,820 --> 00:14:44,039
Right now, it's believed that about 20% of Amazon's packages end up delivered by UPS.

107
00:14:44,039 --> 00:14:52,279
In Colorado, a package destined for the most rural areas, like the western edge of San Miguel County, for example, would take this route.

108
00:14:52,799 --> 00:15:01,840
It would cost Amazon far more, and they'd likely end up losing money on the cheapest items, but it's what's required for them to be able to service every address in the US quickly.

109
00:15:02,679 --> 00:15:07,860
No matter which of these routes a package takes, the end result is, at least hopefully, the same.

110
00:15:07,860 --> 00:15:15,700
UPS, the USPS, or Amazon itself drops off a package at its final destinations after a few days of travel across the US.

111
00:15:16,360 --> 00:15:22,740
It's a very simple process from a consumer perspective, but the behind the scenes is incredibly complex.

112
00:15:23,240 --> 00:15:31,320
The complexity is what's needed, though, for a business whose whole value proposition is to get anything to your door quickly and cheaply.

113
00:15:31,320 --> 00:15:43,240
The core of Amazon, their competitive advantage, is now logistics, to the point where many experts believe that the company will start offering delivery as a service to other companies in the coming years.

114
00:15:43,679 --> 00:15:48,639
They believe that they perfected their system enough that they're going to take on UPS and FedEx.

115
00:15:49,360 --> 00:15:54,820
Of course, Amazon still has competitors which are going after the company as aggressively as ever.

116
00:15:54,820 --> 00:16:03,379
Target, for example, has been able to build a delivery system with similar speed through completely different means, ones that are far simpler.

117
00:16:03,799 --> 00:16:09,360
They've essentially turned each of their 1900 stores across every US state into a fulfillment center.

118
00:16:09,679 --> 00:16:14,940
They send employees out into the aisles who pick, pack, and ship online orders.

119
00:16:14,940 --> 00:16:25,360
That means that their packages never have to travel very far at all, and so they can take advantage of cheap and quick ground shipping from UPS, FedEx, and other more traditional providers.

120
00:16:25,899 --> 00:16:34,820
Some 80% of the company's orders are fulfilled directly from its stores, and now Walmart is also adapting this direct from store fulfillment system as well.

121
00:16:34,820 --> 00:16:50,299
So far though, Amazon believes in their system of simplicity through complexity in their making moves to further expand the system within the US and emulate it in Europe where they recently opened their first air hub in Leipzig and put their first two freight aircraft online in November 2020.

122
00:16:50,879 --> 00:16:58,720
UPS, FedEx, and the other major consumer delivery companies are already well aware of just how big a threat Amazon poses to them.

123
00:16:58,720 --> 00:17:13,920
Amazon has managed to build a 21st century logistics network using 21st century techniques and technologies, and of course part of the threat comes from the company's market dominance, but most is because Amazon is innovating in a way others aren't.

124
00:17:14,339 --> 00:17:27,160
The way FedEx and UPS move packages today is largely the same way they did decades ago, but Amazon's system is only possible through innovations that allow them to manage such a massive, complex, and convoluted system.

125
00:17:27,160 --> 00:17:37,420
This is all to say, if you're worried about Amazon's growing position as the one-stop shop for the world, be worried because they're only getting better at it.

126
00:17:38,720 --> 00:17:44,420
What Amazon's rise proves more than anything is that, like or not, online is the new Main Street.

127
00:17:45,019 --> 00:17:52,440
Therefore, just as you'd be concerned with what your storefront looks like on Main Street, you should be concerned about how your web presence looks.

128
00:17:52,440 --> 00:18:00,799
Now, in the case of email, having a non-custom address is the equivalent of having a dirty sign. It works, but it's not pretty.

129
00:18:01,359 --> 00:18:08,240
That's why you'll notice that most professionals use custom email addresses, something that ends in something like at Wendover.Productions.

130
